{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569532"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22269"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22269"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.41,0.06,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15234"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92248"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1894"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45906"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of worsening lower urinary tract symptoms. He gets up four times a night to pass urine and has a poor stream with hesitancy and terminal dribbling. He has a medical history of hypercholesterolaemia and takes atorvastatin. He does not smoke and drinks about two glasses of wine at weekends. His father died of prostate cancer aged 70.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals no palpable bladder or masses. The general practitioner is concerned that this patient might have prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in his assessment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Digital rectal examination","Prostate specific antigen","Magnetic resonance imaging guided prostate biopsy","Computed tomography of the prostate","Positron emission tomography computed tomography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical lower urinary tract symptoms in the context of a positive family history for prostate cancer, warranting investigation for both benign prostatic hyperplasia and prostate cancer. The most appropriate initial investigation is prostate specific antigen testing, which should ideally be performed before digital rectal examination to avoid false elevation from prostatic manipulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate specific antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line blood test for suspected prostate pathology. It provides valuable baseline information and, combined with clinical assessment, helps determine the need for further investigation. The test should be performed before digital rectal examination as prostatic manipulation can cause transient elevation of prostate specific antigen levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigital rectal examination\u003C/strong\u003E (DRE) used to be considered an important component of prostate assessment and would typically be performed after prostate specific antigen testing. It allows assessment of prostate size, consistency, and the presence of nodules or asymmetry that might suggest malignancy. However, it only provides a palpable assessment of the posterior aspect of the prostate gland, thus missing any tumour that might be present more anteriorly. If clinically significant disease of either 5 - 10% is present, then the increase in detection for prostate cancer with DRE is trivial.  RACGP and Prostate Cancer Foundation of Australia no longer recommends the DRE as a screening tool. This form of examination is considered a stigma by many men and its routine use can act as a deterrent to patients who have prostate symptoms and should be assessed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging guided prostate biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a definitive diagnostic procedure but would only be considered after initial screening investigations suggest possible malignancy. It is not appropriate as a first-line investigation and would typically follow abnormal prostate specific antigen results or suspicious digital rectal examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography of the prostate\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in the initial assessment of suspected prostate cancer. Multiparametric magnetic resonance imaging is the preferred imaging modality when indicated, but imaging is not the first step in assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositron emission tomography computed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E is used for staging in confirmed prostate cancer cases, particularly for detecting metastatic disease. It has no role in the initial diagnostic workup of suspected prostate pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prostate specific antigen testing should be performed before digital rectal examination to avoid false elevation from prostatic manipulation.","Lower urinary tract symptoms in men over 50 with a family history of prostate cancer warrant investigation for both benign prostatic hyperplasia and prostate cancer.","Digital rectal examination and prostate specific antigen are complementary first-line investigations for suspected prostate pathology."],"references":["Rectal Exam a \u201cPoor Test for Prostate Cancer\u201d \u2014 Surgeons and Charity Agree. https://www.baus.org.uk/professionals/baus_business/news/289/rectal_exam_a_poor_test_for_prostate_cancer_surgeons_and_charity_agree","Sandhu S, Moore CM, Chiong E, et al. Prostate cancer. Lancet 2021; 398: 1075\u201390","Guidelines for preventative activities in general practice 10th Edition: Prostate cancer [Internet]. Royal Australian College of General Practitioner. 2024 Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/prostate-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92248"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22269"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92248"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T13:55:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T13:57:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15234"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms"